ct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>Advanced mode supports nested or inherited groups</text><feedback></feedback><correct>1</correct><percent-correct>100</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer></answers><must-select-all>1</must-select-all></question-record><question-record><question>A network administratoris reviewing firewall policies in both interface Pair View and By Sequence View. The policies appear in a different order in each view.
Why is the policy order different in these two views?</question><clue></clue><category></category><weighting>100</weighting><fixed>0</fixed><question-type>1</question-type><answers><answer><text>By sequence View groups policies based on rule prority, while interface pair View always follows the order or traffic logs.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>0</correct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>The firewall dynamically reorders policiesin Interface Pair View based on recent traffic patterns, but By sequence View remains static</text><feedback></feedback><correct>0</correct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>Policies in interface pair View are prioritized by security levels, while By sequence View strictky follows the administrator&apos;s manual ordering.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>0</correct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>Interface Pair Views sorts policies based on matching interfaces, while By Sequence View shows the actual processing order of rules.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>1</correct><percent-correct>100</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer></answers></question-record><question-record><question>An administrator has configured an Application Overrides for the ABC.Com application signature and set the Action to Allow. This application control profile is then applied to a policy that is scanning all outbound traffic. Logging is enabled in the firewall policy. To test the configuration, the administrator accessed the ABC.Com web site several times.Why are there no logs generated under security logs for ABC.Com?  
&amp;#x003C;img src=&quot;31.JPG&quot; alt=&quot;31.JPG&quot; title=&quot;31&quot; width=&quot;356&quot; height=&quot;213&quot;/&amp;#x003E;</question><clue></clue><category></category><weighting>100</weighting><fixed>0</fixed><question-type>1</question-type><answers><answer><text>The ABC.Com Type is set as Application instead of Filter.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>0</correct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>The ABC.Com is configured under application profile, which must be configured as a web filter profile.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>0</correct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>The ABC.Com is hitting the category Excessive-Bandwidth.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>0</correct><percent-correct>0</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer><answer><text>The ABC.Com Action is set to Allow.</text><feedback></feedback><correct>1</correct><percent-correct>100</percent-correct><include-in-mc-options>1</include-in-mc-options></answer></answers></question-record><question-record><question>The predefined deep-inspection and custom-deep-inspection profiles exclude some web categories from SSL inspection, as shown in the exhibit.
